sentence: Yesterday stocks started strong, despite disappointing earnings reports from the likes of Home Depot (HD) and Kohl’s (KSS), and news that the National Transportation Safety Board recommended Boeing (BA) redesign the engine cover on thousands of its 737 planes.

Shares fell shortly after the start however with some of the downward pressure coming from comments made by President Trump during a Cabinet meeting in which he said, “If we don’t make a deal with China, I’ll just raise the tariffs even higher.”

Later in the day, the US Senate passed a Hong Kong rights bill that prompted China to threaten “strong countermeasures” in what is the latest wrinkle in US-China trade talks.

Subsequent reports out of China suggest renewed uncertainty over a US-China trade deal, and this morning US Commerce Secretary Wilbur Ross told Fox Business that trade talks between the U.S. & China are “fluid” with the two countries still “fine-tuning.”

From where we sit, “fluid” does not engender a high degree of confidence and while that could be more gamesmanship at work, the last 24 hours have once again raised questions over not only the scope of a would-be phase-one agreement but its viability as well.
And you thought Groundhog Day only came in February.

In response to this latest trade talk development, Asian equities traded off even though the People's Bank of China lowered its one-year loan prime rate by five basis points to 4.15% and trimmed the five-year loan prime rate to 4.80% from 4.85%.
European stocks are also trading off and are tracking for their worst single-day performance in the last six weeks.
US futures point to a down open despite better than expected retail earnings out this morning.
Earlier today we learned September German Producer Prices fell 0.6% year over year vs. an expected -0.4% drop led by declines for energy and intermediate goods.
The September reading marked the steepest year over year decline since September 2016.
This morning we received MBA Mortgage Applications for the week of November 15th, which fell 2.2% following a 9.6% during the prior week.
The decline was led by the 7.7% fall in refinancing activity, which was offset new home buying applications that climbed 6.7%.

Later today we will get the meeting minutes from the last meeting of the Federal Reserve’s Open Market Committee, better known as the group that makes decisions on raising or lowering the Fed Funds rate.
Given Federal Reserve Chairman Powell’s recent appearance on Capitol Hill, the minutes are likely to contain few surprises.
This morning we will also get an update on inflation in Canada, Russia’s GDP growth rate and Turkey’s central government debt, for those who are just dying for more global economic data to chew on.
Lowe’s (LOW) reported October quarter EPS of $1.41, $0.06 better than the consensus forecast even though revenue dipped year over year and came in a tad below expectations.
Overall comp sales for the quarter rose 2.2%, with comp sales for the US home improvement business up 3.0%, which was below the expected increase of 3.1%.
Lowe’s boosted its 2020 outlook to EPS of $5.63-$5.73 up from the prior $5.45-$5.65.
Lowe's also shared it will close 34 underperforming Canadian stores and rationalize its product offering in Canada.
Target (TGT) shares are trading higher pre-market following quarterly earnings that beat expectations.
The company reported EPS of $1.36, $0.18 ahead of expectations on revenue that essentially matched expectations.
Comp sales for the quarter rose 4.5% on the back of thought year-ago comparisons, with the same happening for Target's digital sales that rose 31% year over year during the quarter.
Same-day fulfillment services accounted for 80% of Target's digital comparable sales growth.
Target boosted its 2020 EPS forecast to $6.25-$6.45 vs. its prior outlook of $5.90-$6.20.

Ahead of today’s 2019 Dreamforce event, Salesforce (CRM) guided its 2020 revenue to$16.99-$17.0 billion and shared its 2021 revenue guidance of $20.8-$20.9 billion and expectation to double its revenue growth over the 2020-20224 period.
Alibaba (BABA) priced a global offering of 500 million in ordinary shares at approximately $180 per ADS.
The BB&T Corp (BBT) - SunTrust Banks (STI) merger has been approved by the Federal Reserve.

Rotating back to retail land, shares of Macy’s (M) dropped 11% yesterday after disappointing results from Kohl’s (KSS), which saw its shares drop 19.5%, left investors worried about consumer spending as we march headlong into the 2019 holiday shopping season.
Shares of Gap Inc (GPS) and Nordstrom (JWN) also were hit by the same concerns, falling 4.6% and 6% respectively.
Urban Outfitters (URBN) reported a miss on both revenue and earnings but better-than-expected same-store sales after the close Wednesday which led to shares dropping over 18% in after-hours trading.
Yesterday TJX Companies (TJX) managed to buck the disappointment trend in retail, beating on revenue, earnings and same-store sales and raised its full-year guidance.
Shares ended yesterday up 1.8%.

The streaming wars are taking their toll on some companies as yesterday Roku (ROKU) announced plans to sell up to 1 million additional shares to raise capital to cover operating expenses, capital expenditures and to fund any future acquisitions.
After having gained nearly 400% in 2019, shares lost nearly 3% during yesterday's trading.

• Fast-food chain Jack in the Box (JACK) is expected to report EPS of $0.96 on revenue of $222.7 million.
• Retail giant L Brands (LB) is expected to report EPS of $0.04 on revenue of $2,690.9 million.
• Lounge comfort king La-Z-Boy (LZB) is expected to deliver EPS of $0.55 on revenue of $454.4 million.
• Wireless speaker maker Sonos (SONO) is expected to report EPS loss of -$0.13 on revenue of $289.1 million.
